Subject#4: Cockerell, Theodore D. A. (Theodore Dru Alison), 1866-1948
Description#1: The 1927 diary for Alice Barringer Mackie chronicles her travels from her home in California to Panama, Antigua, England, Monaco, Italy, Sri Lanka, and Thailand. The time she spent in Asia was primarily travelling with naturalist Theodore Cockerell and his wife, Wilmatte Porter Cockerell, on insect collecting expeditions.
Relation#1: Special Collections, Archives & Preservation, University of Colorado Boulder

Subject#4: Cockerell, Theodore D. A. (Theodore Dru Alison), 1866-1948
Description#1: Beginning the year in Siam (modern day Thailand), Alice describes visiting a variety of places: Bangkok, Angkor Wat, Kuala Lumpur, Singapore, Port Darwin (Australia), Samoa, Hawaii, and ends the year in Redlands, California. She describes how several insects she caught on the Thailand expedition were named after her - Stigmella alicia, as well as Mutilla mackieae.

Subject#4: Cockerell, Theodore D. A. (Theodore Dru Alison), 1866-1948
Description#1: Starting in Redlands, California, Alice describes trips to San Francisco, Denver and Boulder to see Theodore and Wilmatte Cockerell, and on to Washington, D.C. She describes living under Prohibition, and a trip to visit friends in the Caribbean, to Guyana, and then to London, England to finish the year.

Subject#4: Cockerell, Theodore D. A. (Theodore Dru Alison), 1866-1948
Description#1: Alice describes learning to ski in Switzerland before embarking on a journey to Egypt, Greece, and Italy, and then back to England. She describes going to Morocco with Theodore and Wilmatte Cockerell, where they hunted for fossils and insects in the Atlas Mountains.

Subject#4: Cockerell, Theodore D. A. (Theodore Dru Alison), 1866-1948
Description#1: Travelling up the east coast of Africa after a lengthy expedition to gather insects with Theodore Cockerell, John Ogilvie and company in Africa, the journey home takes Alice along the coast of Mozambique, Tanzania, Somalia, Sudan, and through the Suez Canal to Port Said in Egypt. From Egypt, they travel through the Mediterranean to Italy and France. The diary ends in Granada, Spain.

Title#1: Diary of Alice Barringer Mackie: Journal de la Brigade Insecticide
Subject#4: Cockerell, Theodore D. A. (Theodore Dru Alison), 1866-1948
Description#1: This is Alice's account of a ten-month journey with Theodore and Wilmatte Cockerell, and John and Mrs. Ogilvie through Africa to collect insects. They began in Angola, then travelled via railroad and river through the Belgian Congo (now the Democratic Republic of the Congo), Tanzania, Zambia, Zimbabwe, and the diary ends with them in South Africa.
